        public string Article { get; set; } = "<!-- https://localhost:44346/ArticleEngine/Math/quadratic_equation?style=s_math -->\r\n\r\n<h1>Quadratic equation</h1>\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2 id=\"1\">Introduction</h2>\r\n\r\n<p><p>Before we introduce the formulas for solving quadratic equations, let's recall how we have been solving simple equations with one unknown variable <em>x</em> raised to the first power. These were equations similar to the one below.</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"example margin\">\r\n    <div class=\"header\"></div>\r\n    <div class=\"answer\">\r\n        <p style=\"margin-bottom:0px;\"><b>a)</b> \\$5x=x-4 \\$</p>\r\n        <p style=\"margin-bottom:0px;\"><b>b)</b> \\$-2(x-7)+5x=3x+9\\$</p>\r\n        <p style=\"margin-bottom:0px;\"><b>c)</b> \\$x-10=x+7 \\$</p>\r\n    </div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>These types of equations can be reduced to the general form \\$ax + b = 0\\$  or \\$ax = b\\$, where \\$x\\$ is the unknown variable we are solving for, and \\$a\\$ and <em>b</em> are coefficients. We can solve such an equation. Assuming <em>a ≠ 0</em>, we have the solution:</p>\r\n\\[ x = \\frac{-b}{a} \\]\r\n<p>If <em>a = 0</em>, the equation reduces to <em>b = 0</em> and becomes independent of the value of <em>x</em>. For example, if <em>b</em> is also zero, then there are infinitely many solutions.</p>\r\n<p>To summarize, a <strong>linear equation with one unknown</strong> has a single solution when <em>a ≠ 0</em>. If <em>a = 0</em>, it has infinitely many solutions when <em>b = 0</em>, or no solution at all (i.e., it's inconsistent) when <em>b ≠ 0</em>.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"example solve margin\">\r\n    <div class=\"header\"></div>\r\n    <div class=\"content\">Solve equation \\$ -2(x-7)+5x=3x+9\\$</div>\r\n    <div class=\"answer\">\r\n        \\[\\begin{aligned}  -2(x-7)+5x&=3x+9  \\\\ -2x+14+5x&=3x+9 \\ /-14 \\\\ 3x&=3x-5 \\ /-3x \\\\ 0x&=-5 \\\\ 0&=-5  \\end{aligned}\\]\r\n        <p style=\"margin-bottom:0px;\">The equation has no solution. The coefficient \\$a=0\\$ and \\$b=5\\$.</p>\r\n    </div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<h2 id=\"2\">Simple Quadratic Equations \\$ax^2=b\\$ so this is to thest the toc</h2>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Quadratic equations</b> are equations in which the unknown appears in the second power.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We can solve quadratic equations by factoring out a common factor or by using the special product formulas:</p>\r\n\r\n<!-- #############################################################################-->\r\n    [[[VideoItem Code=\"quadratic_equation\"]]]\r\n<!-- #############################################################################-->\r\n\r\n\r\n\\[\r\n\\begin{aligned}\r\na^2 - b^2 &= (a + b)(a - b) \\\\\r\n(a \\pm b)^2 &= a^2 \\pm 2ab + b^2\r\n\\end{aligned}\r\n\\]\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"example\">\r\n    <div class=\"header\"></div>\r\n    <div class=\"answer\">\r\n        Solving the equation \\$x^2=4x\\$ by factoring out \\$x\\$:\r\n        \\[\\begin{aligned} x^2 &= 4x \\\\ x^2 - 4x &= 0 \\\\ x(x-4) &= 0 \\end{aligned}\\]\r\n        We get two solutions:\r\n        \\[\\begin{aligned} x = 0 &\\vee x - 4 = 0 \\\\ x = 0 &\\vee x = 4 \\end{aligned}\\]\r\n    </div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"example\">\r\n    <div class=\"header\"></div>\r\n    <div class=\"answer\">\r\n        Solving the equation \\$7x^2 + 35x = 0\\$ by factoring out \\$7x\\$:\r\n        \\[\\begin{aligned} 7x^2 + 35x &= 0 \\\\ 7x(x+5) &= 0 \\end{aligned}\\]\r\n        We get two solutions:\r\n        \\[\\begin{aligned} 7x = 0 &\\vee x + 5 = 0 \\\\ x = 0 &\\vee x = -5 \\end{aligned}\\]\r\n    </div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"example\">\r\n    <div class=\"header\"></div>\r\n    <div class=\"answer\">\r\n        Solving the equation \\$-3x^2 = 24x\\$ by factoring out \\$-3x\\$:\r\n        \\[\\begin{aligned} -3x^2 &= 24x \\\\ -3x^2 - 24x &= 0 \\\\ -3x(x+8) &= 0 \\end{aligned}\\]\r\n        We get two solutions:\r\n        \\[\\begin{aligned} x \\in \\{ 0, -8 \\} \\end{aligned}\\]\r\n    </div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"example\">\r\n    <div class=\"header\"></div>\r\n    <div class=\"answer\">\r\n        Solving the equation \\$x^2 = 9\\$ using the difference of squares formula\r\n        \\$a^2 - b^2 = (a + b)(a - b)\\$:\r\n        \\[\\begin{aligned}\r\n        x^2 &= 9 \\\\\r\n        x^2 - 9 &= 0 \\\\\r\n        x^2 - 3^2 &= 0 \\\\\r\n        (x + 3)(x - 3) &= 0\r\n        \\end{aligned}\\]\r\n        We get two solutions:\r\n        \\[\\begin{aligned}\r\n        x + 3 = 0 &\\vee x - 3 = 0 \\\\\r\n        x = -3 &\\vee x = 3\r\n        \\end{aligned}\\]\r\n    </div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"example\">\r\n    <div class=\"header\"></div>\r\n    <div class=\"answer\">\r\n        Solving the equation \\$x^2 = 8\\$ using the difference of squares formula\r\n        \\$a^2 - b^2 = (a + b)(a - b)\\$:\r\n        \\[\\begin{aligned}\r\n        x^2 &= 8 \\\\\r\n        x^2 - 8 &= 0 \\\\\r\n        x^2 - (\\sqrt{8})^2 &= 0 \\\\\r\n        (x + \\sqrt{8})(x - \\sqrt{8}) &= 0\r\n        \\end{aligned}\\]\r\n        We get two solutions:\r\n        \\[\\begin{aligned}\r\n        x + \\sqrt{8} = 0 &\\vee x - \\sqrt{8} = 0 \\\\\r\n        x = -\\sqrt{8} &\\vee x = \\sqrt{8}\r\n        \\end{aligned}\\]\r\n    </div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"example solve\">\r\n    <div class=\"header\"></div>\r\n    <div class=\"content\">Solve the equation \\$16x^2 = 5\\$</div>\r\n    <div class=\"answer\">\r\n        \\[\\begin{aligned}\r\n        16x^2 &= 5 \\\\\r\n        x^2 &= \\frac{5}{16} \\\\\r\n        x^2 - \\frac{5}{16} &= 0 \\\\\r\n        x^2 - \\left(\\sqrt{\\frac{5}{16}}\\right)^2 &= 0 \\\\\r\n        x^2 - \\left(\\frac{\\sqrt{5}}{\\sqrt{16}}\\right)^2 &= 0 \\\\\r\n        x^2 - \\left(\\frac{\\sqrt{5}}{4}\\right)^2 &= 0 \\\\\r\n        \\left(x + \\frac{\\sqrt{5}}{4}\\right) \\left(x - \\frac{\\sqrt{5}}{4}\\right) &= 0\r\n        \\end{aligned}\\]\r\n        There are two solutions:\r\n        \\[\\begin{aligned}\r\n        x = -\\frac{\\sqrt{5}}{4} &\\vee x = \\frac{\\sqrt{5}}{4}\r\n        \\end{aligned}\\]\r\n    </div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"example margin\">\r\n    <div class=\"header\"></div>\r\n    <div class=\"answer\">\r\n        Solving the equation \\$x^2 + 6x + 9 = 0\\$ using the special product formula:\r\n        \\$(a + b)^2 = a^2 + 2ab + b^2\\$.\r\n        \\[\\begin{aligned}\r\n        x^2 + 6x + 9 &= 0 \\\\\r\n        x^2 + 2 \\cdot x \\cdot 3 + 3^2 &= 0 \\\\\r\n        (x + 3)^2 &= 0\r\n        \\end{aligned}\\]\r\n        We get one solution:\r\n        \\[\\begin{aligned}\r\n        x + 3 &= 0 \\\\\r\n        x &= -3\r\n        \\end{aligned}\\]\r\n    </div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>As seen from the examples, a quadratic equation can have two solutions.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2 id=\"3\">Quadratic Equation in General Form</h2>\r\n\r\n<!--<article-video video-code=\"s_równanie_kwadratowe_podstawy\"></article-video>-->\r\n<!-- #############################################################################-->\r\n    [[[VideoItem Code=\"s_równanie_kwadratowe_podstawy\"]]]\r\n<!-- #############################################################################-->\r\n\r\n<div class=\"block b-definition\">\r\n    The quadratic equation in general form:\r\n    \\[ ax^2 + bx + c = 0 \\]\r\n    where \\$x\\$ is the unknown, and \\$a\\$, \\$b\\$, and \\$c\\$ are the coefficients, with \\$a \\neq 0\\$.\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"block b-theorem\">\r\n    <p>The quadratic equation can have at most two solutions, which can be calculated using the following formulas.</p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-bottom:0px;\">The formula for the <b>discriminant (delta)</b> of the quadratic equation:</p>\r\n    \\[  \\Delta = b^2 - 4ac  \\]\r\n    <p style=\"margin-bottom:0px;\">The quadratic equation has real solutions (\\$\\mathbb{R}\\$) when \\$\\Delta \\ge 0\\$:</p>\r\n    \\[ x_1 = \\frac{-b + \\sqrt{\\Delta}}{2a} \\quad  x_2 = \\frac{-b - \\sqrt{\\Delta}}{2a} \\]\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"block b-remember\">\r\n    <p style=\"margin-bottom:0px;\">To solve the quadratic equation:</p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-bottom:0px;\"><b>1)</b> Calculate the discriminant \\$\\Delta = b^2 - 4ac\\$.</p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-bottom:0px;\"><b>2)</b> If \\$\\Delta < 0\\$, there are no solutions.</p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-bottom:0px;\"><b>3)</b> If \\$\\Delta = 0\\$, there is one solution.</p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-bottom:0px;\"><b>4)</b> If \\$\\Delta > 0\\$, there are two solutions:</p>\r\n    \\[ x_1 = \\frac{-b + \\sqrt{\\Delta}}{2a} \\quad  x_2 = \\frac{-b - \\sqrt{\\Delta}}{2a} \\]\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"example solve\">\r\n    <div class=\"header\"></div>\r\n    <div class=\"content\">Solve the equation \\$x^2 + 6x + 9 = 0\\$ </div>\r\n    <div class=\"answer\">\r\n        <p style=\"margin-bottom:0px;\">The coefficients are \\$a = 1, b = 6, c = 9\\$.</p>\r\n        \\[\\begin{aligned} \\Delta = 6^2 - 4*1*9 = 36 - 36 = 0 \\end{aligned}\\]\r\n        There is one solution:\r\n        \\[\\begin{aligned} x = \\frac{-6}{2*1} = \\frac{-6}{2} = -3 \\end{aligned}\\]\r\n    </div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"example solve\">\r\n    <div class=\"header\"></div>\r\n    <div class=\"content\">Solve the equation \\$x^2 + 5 = 6x\\$ </div>\r\n    <div class=\"answer\">\r\n        <p style=\"margin-bottom:0px;\">Rearrange the equation to the general form.</p>\r\n        \\[  x^2 - 6x + 5 = 0 \\]\r\n        <p style=\"margin-bottom:0px;\">The coefficients are \\$a = 1, b = -6, c = 5\\$.</p>\r\n        \\[\\begin{aligned} \\Delta = (-6)^2 - 4*1*5 = 36 - 20 = 16 > 0 \\end{aligned}\\]\r\n        There are two solutions, and we have \\$\\sqrt{\\Delta} = 4\\$:\r\n        \\[\\begin{aligned} x_1 = \\frac{-(-6) + 4}{2*1} = \\frac{6 + 4}{2} = \\frac{10}{2} = 5  \\end{aligned}\\]\r\n        \\[\\begin{aligned} x_2 = \\frac{-(-6) - 4}{2*1} = \\frac{6 - 4}{2} = \\frac{2}{2} = 1  \\end{aligned}\\]\r\n    </div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"example solve\">\r\n    <div class=\"header\"></div>\r\n    <div class=\"content\">Solve the equation \\$-2x^2 + 15x + 8 = 0\\$ </div>\r\n    <div class=\"answer\">\r\n        <p style=\"margin-bottom:0px;\">To simplify the calculations, we can multiply both sides of the equation by \\$-1\\$.</p>\r\n        \\[\\begin{aligned}  -2x^2 + 15x + 8 &= 0 \\ /*(-1) \\\\ 2x^2 - 15x - 8 &= 0 \\end{aligned}\\]\r\n        <p style=\"margin-bottom:0px;\">The coefficients are \\$a = 2, b = -15, c = -8\\$.</p>\r\n        \\[\\begin{aligned} \\Delta = (-15)^2 - 4*2*(-8) = 225 + 64 = 289 > 0 \\end{aligned}\\]\r\n        There are two solutions, and we have \\$\\sqrt{\\Delta} = 17\\$:\r\n        \\[\\begin{aligned} x_1 = \\frac{-(-15) + 17}{2*2} = \\frac{15 + 17}{4} = \\frac{32}{4} = 8  \\end{aligned}\\]\r\n        \\[\\begin{aligned} x_2 = \\frac{-(-15) - 17}{2*2} = \\frac{15 - 17}{4} = \\frac{-2}{4} = -\\frac{1}{2}  \\end{aligned}\\]\r\n    </div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n";
